<chapter xml:id="CHAPTERDefiniteIntegration" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Definite Integration</title>
  <section  xml:id="SECTIONCavalierisMethod">
    <title>Historical Precursors to Definite Integration</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        Possibly as a result of the rediscovery of many classical
        Greek works after the fall of <url
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantinople"
        visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantinople">Constantinople</url>
        in 1453,  mathematicians of  the <url
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_Renaissance"
        visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_Renaissance">Italian
        Renaissance</url> began investigating the use of what they
        called <q>indivisibles</q> as a tool for mathematical
        investigations. Today the best known such mathematician was,
        of course, <url
        href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Galileo"
        visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Galileo">Galileo</url>
        whom we have seen before.
      </p>

      <p>
        But the investigations of two others will be of interest to
        us. Both Bonaventura Cavalieri, and Evangelista Torricelli
        were deeply influenced by the work and ideas of Galileo.
      </p>
      <p>
        Torricelli lived with and assisted Galileo during the final
        months of Galileo<rsq/>s life. Cavalieri only met Galileo once
        but they exchanged a long correspondence over the years.  We
        will look closely at Cavalieri<rsq/>s ideas here, and 
        return to Torricelli<rsq/>s in section <xref
        provisional="Torricelli"></xref>.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Historical Context</title>
        <p>
          The concept of an indivisible was vehemently opposed by the
          Catholic Church on religious grounds that are quite
          fascinating. Unfortunately, since our topic is mathematics,
          not religion  discussing them here would take us too far afield.
        </p>
        <p>
          They are discussed in detail in the book, 
          <pubtitle>Infinitesimal</pubtitle>, by Amir Alexander, (2014).
        </p>
      </aside>
    </introduction>


    <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONCavalieri">
      <title>Bonaventura Cavalieri and Indivisibles</title>

      <figure  xml:id="FIGURECavalieri">
        <caption> <url
                      href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Cavalieri/"
                      visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Cavalieri/">Bonaventura
        Cavalieri</url> (1598 <mdash/> 1647)</caption>
        <image source="IC/Cavalieri.png" width="30%">
          <shortdescription>Portrait of Bonaventura Cavalieri</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>

        <url
            href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Cavalieri/"
            visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Cavalieri/">Bonaventura
        Cavalieri</url> was a <url
        href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesuati"
        visual="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jesuati">Jesuat</url>
        monk who studied mathematics at the University of Pisa under
        the tutelage of <url
        href="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Castelli/"
        visual="https://mathshistory.st-andrews.ac.uk/Biographies/Castelli/">Benedetto
        Antonio Castelli</url>. It was Castelli who  introduced Cavalieri to
        Galileo<rsq/>s methods.
        Cavalieri<rsq/>s ideas were deep, fundamental, and direct
        precursors to the notion of a differential so it is worthwhile to
        learn a bit about them before we go on. 
      </p>
      <p>
        In simple terms Cavalieri said that we can compute the area of a
        planar region by summing up <q>all of the lines</q> that make up
        the region. Similarly, we can compute the volume of a solid by
        summing up <q>all of the planes</q> that make it up. An example
        will be helpful.
      </p>


      <example xml:id="EXAMPLECavalierisPrinciple">
        <title>Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle</title>
        <idx><h>Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle</h></idx>

        <p>
          Cavalieri began with the simple observation, seen in <xref
          ref="FIGUREAllLines1"></xref>, that since a rectangle is composed
          of lines, the area of the rectangle is
          equal to the sum of <q>all the lines</q> that make it up.
        </p>

        <figure  xml:id="FIGUREAllLines1">
          <caption>
            Cavalieri asserted that the area of the rectangle is
            composed of (infinitely many) horizontal lines. We have only
            drawn finitely many in this figure and we have  
            separated the lines so they can be seen.
          </caption>
          <image source="IC/CavalieriLines.png" width="20%">
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          He was careful not to say that the area of the rectangle is
          equal to the sum of the <em>areas of the lines</em>. He knew,
          as we do, that this would be problematic since line segments
          do not have an area, and this would have led him into logical
          contradictions.  Instead, like Newton and Leibniz later, he
          simply acknowledged the contradictions and then ignored them,
          proceeding as if line segments do have area.
        </p>
        <p>
          If we accept this premise then clearly any other shape we
          can create using the same lines will have the same area. For
          example the sketch below shows the parallelogram constructed
          from the same lines that make up the rectangle in <xref
          ref="FIGUREAllLines1"></xref>. Clearly both have the same
          area.
        </p>
        <image source="IC/CavalieriLines2.png" width="50%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          Nor is it necessary for the shape to be <q>regular</q>
          in any sense.  The following shapes will also have the same
          area  as long as <q>all the
          lines</q> are the same.
        </p>
        <image source="IC/CavalieriLines3.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          The same idea can be used to compare volumes. For example
          the image below shows two pictures of the same deck of
          cards. Obviously the volumes of the stacks are the same
          since they are made of the same of cards.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <caption></caption>
          <image source="IC/Set.png" >
            <shortdescription></shortdescription>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </example>
      <p>
        Generalizing the ideas in <xref
        ref="EXAMPLECavalierisPrinciple"></xref> slightly gives us
        <term>Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle</term>.
      </p>

      <principle  xml:id="PRINCIPLECavalieri"> 
        <title>Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle</title>
        <statement>
          <p> 
            <idx><h>Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle</h><h>statement of</h></idx>
            If the cross<ndash/>sectional areas of the corresponding
            slices of two solid figures are all in the same
            proportion, say <m>P</m>, then the proportion of the
            volumes of the two figures will also be <m>P</m>
            provided both figures have the same height.
          </p>

        </statement>
      </principle>
      <p>
        For the deck of cards shown above the proportion, <m>P</m>,
        is equal to one. If the cards had been cut in half before
        making the second stack then <m>P=1/2</m> and the second
        stack would have half the volume of the first.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cavalieri  would eventually
        publish his results in a book titled <pubtitle>
        <url href="https://old.maa.org/press/periodicals/convergence/mathematical-treasures-cavalieris-geometry-of-indivisibles" visual="https://old.maa.org/press/periodicals/convergence/mathematical-treasures-cavalieris-geometry-of-indivisibles">Geometria Indivisibilibus</url>
        </pubtitle>.
        Of this Howard Eves<fn> In <pubtitle>Great Moments in Mathematics
        Before 1650</pubtitle></fn> said,
      </p>
      <blockquote> 
        <p>      
          Cavalieri<rsq/>s treatise on the method of
          indivisibles is voluble and not clearly written, and it is
          not easy to learn from it precisely what Cavalieri meant by
          an <lsq/>indivisible<rsq/>.
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        It is likely that this is because Cavalieri was himself unsure
        what an <q>indivisible</q> should be. Nevertheless the
        fundamental notion of an indivisible was picked up by Leibniz
        who transformed it into his <foreign>Calculus
        Differentialis</foreign>.
      </p>

      <problem  xml:id="DRILLCavPrinArea"> 
        <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
        <p>
          <xref ref="PRINCIPLECavalieri">Cavalieri<rsq/>s
          Principle</xref> is normally stated in terms of volumes of
          solids, as we have here, but it is equally applicable to
          the areas of planar regions.
        </p>
        <p>
          State Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle for the area of planar regions.
        </p>
      </problem>

      <example xml:id="EXAMPLECavalieriCircleEllipse"> 
        <title>Circles and Ellipses</title>
        <p>
          To see how Cavalieri used his principle we will find the
          area enclosed by an ellipse by comparing it to the known
          area of a related circle.
        </p>
        
        <p>
          We begin with the graph of
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONCavEllipse">
            \frac{x^2}{a^2}+\frac{y^2}{b^2}=1
          </men>
          which is an ellipse. We then  form the circle
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONCavCircle">
            x^2+y^2=a^2
          </men>
          as shown below.
        </p>

        <image source="IC/CircleAndEllipse.png" width="50%"> 
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>

        <p>
          Solving <xref ref="EQUATIONCavEllipse">equation</xref> for
          <m>y</m> gives 

          <me> y=\frac{b}{a} \sqrt{a^2-x^2} </me>, 

          and solving <xref ref="EQUATIONCavCircle">equation</xref>
          for <m>y</m> gives

          <me> y=\sqrt{a^2-x^2} </me>.  

          Thus the proportion of a typical cross<ndash/>section of
          both figures (see the red, vertical line in the figure) is

          <me> P= \frac{\frac{b}{a} \sqrt{a^2-x^2}}
          {\sqrt{a^2-x^2}}=\frac{b}{a}</me>.

          Therefore by <xref ref="PRINCIPLECavalieri"></xref> the
          ratio of the areas enclosed by the ellipse and the circle is
          also <m>P</m>.  That is

          <me> \frac{\text{Area of Ellipse}}{\text{Area of
          Circle}}=P=\frac{b}{a} </me>.

          Thus,
          since the area of the circle is <m>\pi a^2</m>, 

          <me>
            \text{Area of Ellipse} = \frac{b}{a}(\text{Area of
            Circle}) = \frac{b}{a}(\pi a^2) =\pi ba </me>.

        </p> 
        <p>
          Notice that when <m>a=b</m> the ellipse becomes a circle with radius
          equal to <m>a</m> and our area formula  recovers the area of the
          circle.
        </p>

      </example>

      <exercise xml:id="PROBLEMVolSphereCavalieri">
        

        <introduction>
          <p>
            To display the power and usefulness of Cavalieri<rsq/>s Principle we
            will use it to find the formula for the volume of a sphere with radius
            <m>r</m>.
          </p>
          <sidebyside widths="35% 35%" margins="auto" valign="middle">
            <figure  xml:id="FIGUREHalfSphere">
              <caption>Half of a sphere with radius <m>r</m>.</caption>
              <image source="IC/HalfSphere.png" width="100%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
              </image>
            </figure>

            <figure  xml:id="FIGURECylSansCone">
              <caption>A cylinder with radius <m>r</m> with a cone removed.</caption>
              <image source="IC/CylSansCone.png" width="100%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
              </image>
            </figure>
          </sidebyside>


        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that the red circle in <xref ref="FIGUREHalfSphere"></xref> has
              the same area as the red annulus in <xref
              ref="FIGURECylSansCone"></xref>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>

        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Show that the volume of the solid in <xref
              ref="FIGURECylSansCone"></xref> is <m>\frac23 \pi r^3</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <hint>
            <p>
              You will need a formula for the volume of the cylinder and a formula
              for the volume of the cone deleted from it.

            </p>
          </hint>

        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Use <xref ref="PRINCIPLECavalieri">Cavalieri<rsq/>s
              Principle</xref> to conclude that the volume of a
              sphere with radius <m>r</m> is <m>\frac43 \pi r^3</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
      </exercise>

    </subsection>

    <subsection  xml:id="SUBSECTIONCavLeibNotation">
      <title>Cavalieri, Differentials, and Definite Integration</title>
      <p>
        In view of our discussion in <xref
        ref="SECTIONThinkingAboutIntegration"></xref> it should be
        clear that the <q>indivisibles</q> Cavalieri<rsq/>s is
        <q>adding up</q> are the same things as Leibniz<rsq/>
        differentials so we will adjust our point of view
        accordingly. In <xref ref="FIGUREAllLines1"></xref> for
        example, instead of thinking of the <q>lines</q> as line
        segments with zero width we think of them as having a
        differential width <m>\dx{x}\neq 0</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In that case a rectangle consists of <q>all the lines</q> with
        differential area: <me>(\text{length})\times\dx{x}</me>. Using the
        summation notation we saw in
        <xref ref="SECTIONThinkingAboutIntegration"></xref> the area
        of a rectangle is thus given by the integral
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONCavRect">\int(\text{length})\dx{x}</men>. Notice that since the quantity,
        <m>(\text{length}) \times \dx{x}</m> is a
        differential (as we observed in <xref
        ref="DIGRESSIONDifferentialNotation"
        text="custom">Differential Notation</xref>) <xref
        ref="EQUATIONCavRect">formula</xref> has exactly the same form
        as an integral, as defined in <xref
        ref="SECTIONThinkingAboutIntegration"></xref>, it appears that
        we can compute the area of this rectangle , if only we can find a way
        to compute the integral <m>\int \text{(length)}\dx{x}</m>.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Comment</title>
        <p>
          Yes we know this area can be found by simpler means. We don<rsq/>t care
          about that. We want to find a way to <em>express</em> this
          simple area using the integral notation so that we can
          write down expressions for more complicated areas and,
          hopefully, find ways to compute them. Stick with
          us. We<rsq/>re just getting started.
        </p>
        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   In fact, ultimately we don<rsq/>t really care (much) about -->
        <!--   computing areas <foreign>per se</foreign>. For us the -->
        <!--   problem of computing area is just a relatively simple -->
        <!--   context in which we can develop the skills that will help -->
        <!--   us compute other quantities that we do care about. -->
        <!-- </p> -->
      </aside>


      <p>
        But the notation we<rsq/>ve used here isn<rsq/>t quite as
        useful, or expressive as we<rsq/>d like so we will pause for a
        moment to refine our notation.  
        Suppose we want to compute the area of the rectangle in the
        sketch below using an integral.
        </p>
        <image source="IC/RectangleAreaDiff.png" width="60%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          In our sketch the red line represents one of the Cavalieri
          lines to be summed.
          <!-- Each such line has a height of <m>2</m> -->
          <!-- and a width of <m>\dx{x}</m> so we need to add up the -->
          <!-- contribution of each line to the total area.  -->
          Observe that if <m>A</m> represents the area of the
          rectangle in black then <m>\dx{A}=2\dx{x}</m>. That is, the
          quantity <m>2\dx{x}</m> is the differential of the area
          <m>A</m>. So to compute <m>A</m> we need to find a way to
          compute the sum
          <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntCav">
            A=\int\dx{A}=\int 2\dx{x}
          </men>
          starting at <m>x=2</m> and ending at <m>x=6</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          There are two problems with the notation we used in <xref
          ref="EQUATIONIntCav">equation</xref>.

          <dl>
            <li>
              <title>First Problem:</title>
              <p>
                <xref ref="EQUATIONIntCav">Equation</xref> does not
                reflect the fact that we begin summing our differentials
                at <m>x=2</m> and end at <m>x=6</m>. If we stick with this
                notation then another rectangle with other beginning and
                ending points would be written in exactly the same
                way. We will find it useful to reduce this ambiguity by
                specifying the interval <m>(2,6)</m> within our definite integral
                notation.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <title>Second Problem:</title>
              <p>
                The notation in <xref
                ref="EQUATIONIntCav">equation</xref> is exactly the same
                notation we used in <xref
                ref="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsAntiDerivative"></xref> to
                designate the most general antiderivative (multifunction).
              </p>
            </li>
          </dl>
        </p>
        <p>
          The purpose of notation is to clarify not to befuddle. A
          notation that can be read as either a number (the area of a
          rectangle in this case) or as an antiderivative, depending
          on the context of the discussion is not an ideal notation.
        </p>

        <aside>
          <title>Comment</title>
          <p>
            To be sure, just as there are words in English with more
            than one meaning, there are also symbols in mathematics
            with more than one meaning. 
            <!-- The problem can<rsq/>t be -->
            <!-- avoided entirely -->
            This flexibility and redundancy is what gives English
            its beauty and expressive power.
            But in mathematics it just leads to unnecessary confusion,
            and is best avoided if possible.
            </p>
        </aside>
        <p>
          We<rsq/>d like to have a notation that
          reflects the fact that
          the antiderivative and the area computation are
          related (both are built from the summation of
          differentials), but at the same time clearly distinguishes
          between them.   It will  take a while to build up all of the
          necessary ideas so  be patient.
        </p>
        <p>
          We  can address the second problem by simply reserving the
          notation <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m> for the most general
          antiderivative as we originally used it.  We make the
          following definition.
        </p>
        <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONIndefInt">
          <title>The Most General Antiderivative</title>
          <idx><h>Integral</h><h>Indefinite</h></idx>
          
          <statement>
            <p>
              Given the function <m>f(x)</m> the formula <me>\int
              f(x)\dx{x}</me> <em>always</em> represents the
              multifunction whose derivative is <m>f(x)</m> <mdash/>
              the <term>most general antiderivative</term>.
            </p>
            
            <p>
              In particular, if <m>F(x)</m> is any antiderivative of
              <m>f(x)</m> Then
              <men xml:id="EQUATIONIndefIntDef">\int f(x)\dx{x} = F(x)
              +C</men>, where, as before, <m>C</m> represents all possible constants.
            </p>
            <!--   <p> -->
            <!--     For simplicity, and because it has become standard, we will -->
            <!--     almost always refer to  <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m> as the  -->
            <!--     <term>indefinite integral</term> of <m>f(x)</m>, rather -->
            <!--     than as a multifunction. -->
            <!--   </p> -->
            <!--   <p> -->
            <!--     Because <m>f(x)</m> and <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m> are so -->
            <!--     closely related it is common to define <me>F(x)=\int -->
            <!--     f(x)\dx{x}</me> and call <m>F(x)</m> the indefinite -->
            <!--     integral of <m>f(x)</m>, just because it is less to write. -->
            <!--   </p> -->
          </statement>
        </definition>
        <p>
          <xref ref="DEFINITIONIndefInt">Definition</xref>
          formalizes the work we did in <xref
          ref="CHAPTERApplicaitonsOfIntegration"></xref>, and
          establishes  the notation we used there as the standard
          notation for an antidifferentiaton. Our next
          definition is new. It will establish the standard notation we will use
          to distinguish the antiderivative problems in <xref
          ref="CHAPTERApplicaitonsOfIntegration"></xref> and the area
          problem  in <xref ref="EQUATIONIntCav">equation</xref>, as well
          as other kinds of problems that can be addressed using the
          same ideas. Since the underlying ideas are related the
          notations we use will also be related. You<rsq/>ll need to
          read the notation carefully to be sure you understand which
          kind of problem you are looking at.
        </p>

        <!-- <p> -->
        <!--   To address the first problem we modify the notation for -->
        <!--   <xref ref="DEFINITIONIndefInt"></xref> slightly so as to -->
        <!--   indicate where to start and where to stop summing the -->
        <!--   differentials. -->
        <!-- </p> -->

        <p>
          We learned in <xref ref="SECTIONGalileoDrops"></xref> that
          the velocity of an object moving in a straight line is the
          derivative of its position.  Recasting the previous sentence
          in the language of integrals we
          it says that the position of the object is the integral of its
          velocity. But when we view the the problem from this
          direction things are complicated by the presence of the
          <q><m>+C</m></q> from <xref
          ref="EQUATIONIndefIntDef">equation</xref>.
        </p>

        <p>
          <!-- <m>p(t_1)=p_1 p(t_2)=p_2</m><m>0</m> -->

          To understand how to deal with this difficulty suppose that
          we are traveling in a straight line (say, from left to right
          along the <m>x</m><mdash/>axis) with velocity <m>v(t)
          \frac{\text{miles}}{\text{hour} }</m> and we<rsq/>d like to
          find out how far we travel between the times <m>t=t_1</m>
          and <m>t=t_2</m> as shown in the following sketch.
        </p>
        <image source="IC/IntPosVel.png" width="80%">
          <shortdescription></shortdescription>
        </image>
        <p>
          If we suppose that our positions at <m>t_1</m> and
          <m>t_2</m> are <m>p_1</m> and <m>p_2</m> respectively , then
          the distance, <m>D</m>, that we travel between those times
          is clearly <me>D=p_2-p_1</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          So far, so good. Do you see how we find <m>p_1</m> and
          <m>p_2</m>? Recall that these are our positions, and we have
          know the   position function. It is <m>\int
          v(t)\dx{t}</m>,  an antiderivative 
          of velocity. So to find <m>p_1</m>
          and <m>p_2</m>   all we have to do is evaluate
          <me>
            \eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_1}\text {and} \eval{\int
            v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_2} </me>.

        </p>
        <p>
          Well, sort of.
        </p>
        <p>
          Remember that <m>\int v(t)\dx{t}</m> is a
          multifunction. That is, it is a lot of related functions
          gathered together in a single package. We need to find the
          one function in the package that reflects the problem at
          hand before we can evaluate it. So we take <m>P(t)</m> to be
          the antiderivative of <m>v(t)</m>
          <!--  so that -->
          <!-- <me> -->
          <!--   \dfdx{P}{t}=v(t) -->
          <!--   </me>, and that         -->
          with the following values:
            <m>
              P(t_1)=p_1
              </m>
              and
              <m>
                P(t_2)=p_2
                </m>.
                Clearly then
                <me>D=p_2-p_1=P(t_2)-P(t_1)</me>.
        </p>
        <p>
          There is something interesting here that may not be quite
          visible yet. To see it suppose that <m>\hat{P}(t)</m> is
          some other antiderivative of <m>v(t)</m>. From our work in
          <xref ref="CHAPTERIntSimplest"></xref> that
          <m>\hat{P}(t)=P(t)+C</m> where in this case <m>C</m> is some
          fixed constant. Clearly then
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \hat{P}(t_2)-\hat{P}(t_1)\amp{}=\left( P(t_2)+C\right)-\left(
              P(t_1)+C\right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{} = P(t_2)-P(t_1)+\underbrace{C-C}_{=0}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{} = p_2-p_1
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp{}=D.
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      <p>
        In other words it doesn<rsq/>t matter which specific
        antiderivative we choose from the multifunction <m>\int
        v(t)\dx{t}</m>. Because we are subtracting its value at two
        different values of <m>t</m> the constant <m>C</m> that is
        common to both evaluations will simply subtract away.  If this
        is hard to see right now don<rsq/>t worry.  Our discussion has
        been fairly general and abstract which can often obscure the
        point. Once you have done <xref
        ref="DRILLVerifyAnyAntiDeriv"></xref> below you will see that
        it is actually a simple idea.
      </p>

<p>
  Summarizing our discussion so far we see that
  <men xml:id="EQUATIONFTCBadNotation">
    D= \eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_2} - \eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_1}
  </men>
  Strictly speaking <xref
  ref="EQUATIONFTCBadNotation">equation</xref> is a slight abuse of
  our notation since we really mean that we are choosing one
  antiderivative from the most general antiderivative and evaluating
  it. Because the constant will subtract out it doesn<rsq/>t
  matter which one we choose.
</p>



<!-- <p> -->
<!--   The problem now is, if <m>P(t)</m> is one of the antiderivatives how -->
<!--   do we compute <m>P(t_1)</m> and <m>P(t_2)</m>? -->
<!-- </p> -->




<!-- <p> -->
<!--   Clearly this will be the -->
<!--   value of the definite integral  -->
<!--   <me>\int_{t_1}^{t_2}v(t) \dx{t}</me> but we don<rsq/>t yet -->
<!--   know how to compute that. How else might we find the distance? -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!--   We need to be able to specify when the point has a given -->
<!--   position so we<rsq/>ll assume we have a stopwatch that we -->
<!--   can start whenever we want to. At some point to the left of -->
<!--   <m>t_1</m> we           Normally we would call this point the origin          At a point we<rsq/>ll call the origin to the left of -->
<!--   <m>t_0</m> we start a clock. So the origin is the point -->
<!--   where <m>t=0</m>. -->
<!-- </p> -->

<!-- <p> -->
<!--   We can find the distance -->
<!--   traveled in the interval <m>[t_0, t_1]</m> by summing the -->
<!--   distance traveled at each instant of travel. -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!--   That is, we assume that time consists of infinitesimal -->
<!--   moments we<rsq/>ll call <m>\dx{t}</m>. At time <m>t</m> -->
<!--   the velocity will be constantly equal to <m>v(t)</m>. When -->
<!--   the velocity is constant we know that -->
<!--   <me> -->
<!--     \text{(D)istance } = \text{(R)ate }\times \text{(T)ime} -->
<!--     </me>. -->
<!--     Therefore the differential of the distance -->
<!--     traveled during a given  instant <m>\dx{t}</m> will be -->
<!--     <me>\dx{D} = v(t)\dx{t}</me>. -->

<!--     Summing both sides between <m>t_0</m> and <m>t_1</m> we -->
<!--     see that the total distance traveled can be expressed as  -->
<!--     <me>D=\int_{t=t_0}^{t_1}\dx{D} = \int_{t=t_0}^{t_1} v(t)\dx{t}</me>. -->
<!--     <!-\- <me>D(t_0)-D(t_0) = \int_{t=t_0}^{t_0}v(t)\dx{t}</me>. -\-> -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!--   To see how to evaluate this integral directly suppose we -->
<!--   know that at time <m>t=0</m> (when we start our clock) we have already moved -->
<!--   five miles from our starting point so -->
<!--   <me>\eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{0}=5</me>. Thus the distance -->
<!--   function  -->
<!--   <me>S(t)=\int v(t)\dx{t} +5</me> will give -->
<!--   our position at any time <m>t</m>. -->
<!--   To find the distance we travel from the start time to -->
<!--   <m>t_0</m> we need to compute  -->
<!--   <me>S(t_0)=\eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_0} +5</me>. To -->
<!--   find the distance we travel from the start time to -->
<!--   <m>t_1</m> we need to compute  -->
<!--   <me>S(t_1)=\eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_1} +5</me>. -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->

<!--   All this -->
<!--   <m>\int v(t)\dx{t} </m>, where  -->
<!--   <me>S(0)=</me>            says is that  -->
<!-- </p> -->
<!-- <p> -->
<!--   Our position at time <m>t=t_0</m> will then be -->
<!--   <me>S(t_0)=\eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_0}</me> and our -->
<!--   position at time <m>t=t_1</m> is -->
<!--   <me>S(t_1)=\eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{t_1}</me>. -->
<!-- </p> -->
<p>
  The discussion above has been quite dense. It is laden
  with both new ideas and  new notation.
  Let<rsq/>s use <xref
  ref="EQUATIONFTCBadNotation">equation</xref> to solve a very
  simple problem <mdash/> one where we already know the
  answer <mdash/> and verify that it all makes sense.
</p>


<example xml:id="EXAMPLEVelAndPos">
  
  <p>
    Suppose we are traveling on a straight road at <m>60
    \frac{miles}{hour}</m>. How far do we travel between the
    third hour and the eighth hour?
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course you see that if we travel for five hours at <m>60
    \frac{\text{miles}}{\text{hour}}</m> then we travel <m>5\times 60 =
    300</m> miles.
  </p>
  <p>
    In this problem our velocity is <m>v(t)=60</m>, <m>t_1=3</m>,
    and <m>t_2=8</m>. So the distance traveled will be <me>
    D= \eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{5} - \eval{\int
    v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{3}</me>.
    One antiderivative of <m>v(t)=60</m> is
    <m>P(t)=60t</m>, so
    <me>
      D= \eval{60t}{t}{8} - \eval{60t}{t}{3} = 60\cdot8-60\cdot3=300
      </me>.
  </p>
</example>

<problem xml:id="DRILLVerifyAnyAntiDeriv">
  <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
  <p>
    Find two different antiderivatives of <m>v(t)=60</m> in <xref
    ref="EXAMPLEVelAndPos"></xref> and show that
    <me>
      \eval{\int v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{5} - \eval{\int
      v(t)\dx{t}}{t}{3}=300</me> using your antiderivatives.
  </p>
</problem>
<p>
  While expressive, the notation
  <me>
    \eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}-\eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{b}
  </me>
  is too redundant. The only difference between the first
  and second term is that <m>x=a</m> changes to
  <m>x=b</m>. So, because mathematicians won<rsq/>t write
  two symbols when one will do, we extend the evaluation notation introduced in <xref
  ref="EvaluationNotation" text="custom"> Evaluation
  Notation</xref> as follows: 
  <me>
    \eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}^b = \eval{\int
    f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}-\eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{b} </me>.
</p>
<p>
  Be sure you understand this notation. There is a lot here. The
  formula <m>\int f(x)\dx{x}</m> represents the most general
  antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>. Think of it a all of the
  antiderivatives gathered together in a single package. We select one of the
  antiderivatives for evaluation  when we
  evaluate it at <m>x=a</m> and <m>x=b</m>. It doesn<rsq/>t matter
  which one we select because they are all the same except for the
  arbitrary constant <m>C</m>, and it will be subtracted off when we
  compute the difference.
  This
  suggests the following definition.
  </p>
  <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONDefInt">
    <title>Definite Integral</title>
    <idx><h>Integral</h><h>Definite</h></idx>
    
    <statement>
      <p>
        Given a function <m>f(x)</m>, the formula <men
        xml:id="EQUATIONDefInt">\int_{x=a}^{b} f(x)\dx{x}</men>
        represents the sum of all of the differentials of the form
        <m>f(x)\dx{x} </m> beginning at <m>x=a</m> and ending at
        <m>x=b</m>. Such an expression is called a
        <term>definite integral</term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
  <p>
    The following theorem summarizes our discussion above. It states how
    a definite integral can be evaluated.
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="THEOREMEvaluateDefInt">
    <p>
      The definite integral
      can be evaluated by computing 
      <mdn>
        <mrow number="no">
          \int_{x=a}^{b} f(x)\dx{x}\amp{}= \eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}^b
        </mrow>
        <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONDefIntDefinition1">
          \amp{} = \eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}-\eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{b}.
        </mrow>
      </mdn>

      <!-- <men xml:id="EQUATIONDefIntDefinition1"> -->
      <!--   \int_{x=a}^{b} f(x)\dx{x}= -->
      <!--   \eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}^b =        \eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{a}-\eval{\int f(x)\dx{x}}{x}{b}  -->
      <!--   </men>. -->
    </p>

    <p>
      Often we will have a formula, say <m>F(x)</m>, for one of the
      antiderivatives of <m>f(x)</m> in the most general antiderivative <m>\int
      f(x)\dx{x}</m>. In that case <xref
      ref="EQUATIONDefIntDefinition1">equation</xref> reduces to 
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONDefIntDefinition2">
        \int_{x=a}^b f(x)\dx{x} = F(b)-F(a)
      </men>
    </p>
  </theorem>


  <p>
    The subscripts and superscripts on the integral symbol  in <xref
    ref="EQUATIONDefInt">equation</xref> are called the upper
    and lower <term>indices</term>.  Take careful note that we evaluate
    the antiderivative at the lower index and subtract from it the
    result of evaluating at the upper index. What happens if you do it
    backwards?
  </p>
  <aside>
    <title>Note to self</title>
    <p>
      We need a bunch of definite integral drills here. These can be at varying
      levels of difficulty depending on what<rsq/>s been covered in <xref
      ref="CHAPTERIntSimplest"></xref> .
    </p>
  </aside>


  <exercise>
    <title>Find the Pattern</title>
    
    <task>
      <p>
        Show that each of the following statements is true.
        <ol cols="2" marker="(i)">
          <li>
            <m>\int_{x=0}^1x \dx{x}=\frac12 </m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int_{x=0}^1x^2 \dx{x}=\frac13 </m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int_{x=0}^1x^3 \dx{x}=\frac14 </m>
          </li>
          <li>
            <m>\int_{x=0}^1x^4 \dx{x}=\frac15 </m>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        Use the pattern you observed in part (a) to predict the value
        of  
        <md>
          <mrow>
            \int_{x=0}^1x^\alpha  \dx{x}\amp{}\amp{} \text{ where } \alpha \gt 0 
          </mrow>
        </md> 
        then show that your
        prediction is true.
      </p>
    </task>
    <task>
      <p>
        What happens if <m>\alpha \le 0</m>?
      </p>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <!-- <definition xml:id="DEFINITIONDefInt"> -->
