<!-- </subsection> -->
</section>


<section xml:id="SECTIONInDefInt">
  <title>Accumulation: The Indefinite Integral</title>
  <p>
    In this section We will introduce the last variation on the
    integration notation we will use in this text.
  </p>

  <p>
    We will need the following lemma about definite
    integrals, which we state without proof.
  </p>
  <lemma xml:id="LEMMAIntegalAtPointIsZero">
    
    <p>
      If <m>f(t)</m> is integrable and <m>a</m> is in the
      domain of <m>a</m>, then <me>\displaystyle \int_{t=a}^af(t)\dx{t}
      =0</me>.
    </p>
  </lemma>
  <p>
    Eventually <xref ref="LEMMAIntegalAtPointIsZero"></xref> will have
    to be proved rigorously. But  you can see that it must be true
    since we start, and stop,  integrating at the same point,
    <m>t=a</m>. So there is nothing to sum up, the integral must be 
    zero.  
  </p>  
  <p>
    To begin defining the <term> indefinite integral</term> observe
    that we can find the shaded area in <xref
    ref="FIGUREIntegralAsFunction"></xref> by summing all
    differentials of the form <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> from <m>t=a</m> to
    <m>t=b</m>. It follows that the definite integral
    <m>\int_{t=a}^bf(t) \dx{t}</m> represents that area.
  </p>
  <figure  xml:id="FIGUREIntegralAsFunction">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="IC/IntegralAsFunction.png" width="70%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>
  <p>
    Similarly, the integral <m>\int_{t=a}^{x_1} f(t)\dx{t}</m>
    represents the shaded area between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=x_1</m>, 
    <m>\int_{t=a}^{x_2} f(t)\dx{t}</m>
    represents the shaded area between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=x_2</m>, 
    <m>\int_{t=a}^{x_3} f(t)\dx{t}</m>
    represents the shaded area between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=x_3</m>,
    and in general
    <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntegralAsFunction">
      \int_{t=a}^{x} f(t)\dx{t}
    </men>
    represents the shaded area between <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=x</m>. An
    integral like the one in <xref
    ref="EQUATIONIntegralAsFunction">formula</xref> is called an 
    <term>indefinite integral</term> because it<rsq/>s value depends
    on the location of <m>x</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    But we already have a term for this kind of dependency. When the
    value of one quantity depends on the value of another the first is
    said to be a <term> function </term> of the second. Thus we see
    that the <term>indefinite integral</term> in <xref
    ref="EQUATIONIntegralAsFunction">formula</xref> represents a
    function of <m>x</m>.
  </p>


  <p>
    Because we<rsq/>ve built the function <me>\int_{t=a}^xf(t)\dx{t}
    \text{ (note the presence of indices)}
    </me> by summing differentials in exactly the same way we built the
    most general antiderivative <me>\int f(t)\dx{t} \text{ (note the
    absence of indices)}</me>, it should be clear that
    <m>\int_{t=a}^xf(t)\dx{t}</m> is one of the antiderivatives of
    <m>f(t)</m>. 
  </p>

  <problem>
    <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
    <p>
      Can you see  which antiderivative it is? Take your best guess
      before reading on.
    </p>
  </problem>
  <p>
    The integral form of a function is cumbersome so we will only use
    it when there is a compelling need. Otherwise we<rsq/>ll just
    choose a name for the function as usual.  For instance we would
    use <m>F(x)</m> to name the function defined by <xref
    ref="EQUATIONIntegralAsFunction">formula</xref> giving 

    <men xml:id="EQUATIONFuncFromInt"> F(x) = \int_{t=a}^{x} f(t)\dx{t} </men>.
    
    This allows us to distinguish
    between <m>F(x)</m> and <m>f(x)</m>, while also indicating that
    they are related.
  </p>
  <p>
    We only know one other fact about
    <m>F(x)=\int_{t=a}^xf(t)\dx{t}</m> aside from the fact that it is
    an antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m>. From <xref
    ref="LEMMAIntegalAtPointIsZero"></xref> we know that <me>F(a) =
    \int_{t=a}^af(t)\dx{t}=0 </me>. There can be only one
    antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m> with this property because any other
    would differ by some fixed amount, <m>C</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    So there it is. The function denoted by <m>F(x)=\int_{t=a}^xf(t)
    \dx{t}</m> is the unique antiderivative of <m>f(x)</m> with the
    property that when it is evaluated at <m>x=a</m> we get zero. A
    specific example will help clarify all of this.
  </p>
  <example xml:id="EXAMPLESimpleIndefInt">
    <title>A Simple Indefinite Integral: Finding the Constant</title>
    <p>
      Suppose we define <m>F(x)</m> as 
      <men xml:id="EQUATIONSimpleIndef">F(x) = \int_{t=2}^x
      3t\dx{t}</men>. We know that <m>\hat{F}(x) = \frac32x^2</m>
      is an antiderivative of <m>f(x)=3x</m>. But
      <m>\hat{F}(2)=6\neq{}0</m>, so this  is  not
      antiderivative we are searching for. 
    </p>
    <p>
      However, because all of the antiderivatives of <m>f(x)=3x</m>
      differ by a constant it must be that 
      <me>F(x)=\hat{F}(x)+C=\frac32x^2+C </me> for some value of <m>C</m>. To find
      <m>C</m> we recall that <m>F(2)=0</m>. Thus
      <me>
        F(2)=0{}=\eval{\frac32x^2+C}{x}{2} = \frac32\cdot 2^2+C
        </me>.
        Therefore <m>C=-6 </m> and thus
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONSimpleIndefSolution">F(x)=\frac32x^2-6 </men>.
    </p>
  </example>
  <p>
    Because <xref ref="EQUATIONSimpleIndefSolution">formula</xref>
    is more familiar than <xref
    ref="EQUATIONSimpleIndef">formula</xref> it is tempting to
    think of <m>F(x)=\frac32x^2-6</m> as the <q>correct</q> formula
    for <m>F(x)</m> and to think of <m>\int_{t=2}^x 3t\dx{t}</m> as
    an intermediate step in finding <m>F(x)</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This is a fundamentally flawed view. In the same way that
    <m>2</m>, <m>\sqrt{4}</m>, <m>\frac{6}{3} </m>, or even
    <m>\csc\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) </m> are all alternative
    representations of the number two, <xref
    ref="EQUATIONSimpleIndefSolution">formula</xref> and <xref
    ref="EQUATIONSimpleIndef">formula</xref> are two alternative ways
    to designate the function <m>F(x)</m>. They mean the same thing
    and which you choose to use will depend on your needs at the
    moment.
  </p>
  <p>
    Of course in the absence of some specific need most people will
    use <xref ref="EQUATIONSimpleIndefSolution">formula</xref>
    because it is simpler to read and write, in the same way that we
    would use <q><m>2</m></q> unless there was some compelling
    reason not to.
  </p>
  <example xml:id="EXAMPLEGaussianDistribution">
    <title>A Compelling Need</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>f(t)=e^{-x^2}</m> is an integrable function the
      function <me>{\cal G}(x)=\int_{t=0}^xe^{-x^2}\dx{t} </me> is
      well defined. However there is no known simple algebraic formula
      for this function. The only notation we have for it is the one
      we<rsq/>ve just shown you. Nevertheless <m>{\cal G}(x)</m> is an
      important function in, among other things, statistical
      analysis. It<rsq/>s graph  is the 
      <term>
        bell curve
      </term>
      you may have heard of. Here is its graph:
      </p>
      <image source="IC/GaussDist.png" width="70%">
      <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
    </example>

    <p>
      The computations in <xref
      ref="EXAMPLESimpleIndefInt">Example</xref> should feel very
      familiar to you. You<rsq/>ve done this kind of thing before. But
      when we solved the problems in <xref ref="DRILLIVP-sqr"></xref>
      in <xref ref="SECTIONDEsandIVPS"></xref>, for instance, we
      already knew that the derivative of <m>x^2</m> is <m>2x</m>.  So
      all we had to do was satisfy the initial values. We now have the
      tools we need to solve an IVP without any prior knowledge of the
      solution.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="EXAMPLESomeIVPsIntNotation">
      <title>Some Initial Value Problems</title>

      <task xml:id="EXAMPLESomeIVPsIntNotationA">
        <p>
          For example, if we want to solve the IVP
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \dfdx{y}{x}=\cos(x), \text{ } y(0)=-2.
            </mrow>
          </md>
          we proceed as follows.
        </p>
        <p>
          We need an antiderivative of <m>\cos(x) </m>. One
          antiderivative is <me>y(x) = \int_{t=0}^x\cos(t)\dx{t}</me>
          but this is not the one we need since <m>Y(0)=0\neq -2</m>.
          It should be clear that <me>y(x) =
          \int_{t=0}^x\cos(t)\dx{t}-2</me> is the correct solution.
          But it is not very useful in this form because we have no
          way to evaluate <m>y(x)</m> for any value of <m>x</m> other
          than <m>x=0</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Let<rsq/>s look for something a little more useful.  We know
          that <m>\sin(x) </m> is an antiderivative of <m>\cos(x)
          </m>. But <m>\sin(x) </m> does not satisfy our initial
          condition (since <m>\sin(0)=0\neq-2 </m>) so we need one of the
          other antiderivatives of <m>\cos(x) </m>.  We
          don<rsq/>t know which one so we<rsq/>ll say that <me>y(x) =
          \sin(x) +C</me> and look for the value of <m>C</m> that
          works. Thus the solution of our IVP must be <me>y(x) =
          \sin(x)-2 </me>.
        </p>
      </task>

      <task xml:id="EXAMPLESomeIVPsIntNotationB">
        <p>
          Of course we could have solved the IVP in part (a) by guessing
          just like we did before. Let<rsq/>s look at an example that we
          can<rsq/>t solve by guessing.
          Let<rsq/>s solve the IVP 
          <me>\dfdx{y}{x}= \int \pi e^x\sin(\pi{}e^x) \dx{x}, \text{ } y(0)=7</me>. 
        </p>
          <p>
            First we need an antiderivative of <m>\pi
            e^x\sin(\pi{}e^x)</m>. Using the techniques we learned in <xref
            ref="SECTIONSubstMethed"></xref> we see that one
            antiderivative is <m>y(x)=-\cos(\pi e^x) </m>. As usual
            this is the wrong one so we set
            <m>y(x)=-\pi\cos(\pi{}e^x)+C</m> and try to find the value of
            <m>C</m> that works. This is clearly 
            <me>y(x)=-\cos (\pi e^x)+6</me>.
          </p>
      </task>
      
    </example>
    <problem>
      <idx><h>Drills</h></idx>
      <p>
        Using the techniques we learned in <xref
        ref="SECTIONSubstMethed"></xref> to show that
        <m>y(x)=-\cos(\pi e^x) </m> is an antiderivative of <m> \pi
        e^x\sin(\pi{}e^x) </m> as we claimed in <xref
        ref="EXAMPLESomeIVPsIntNotationB"></xref>.
      </p>
    </problem>



    <!-- <p> -->
    <!--   More generally, it represents the function which, given the -->
    <!--   input <m>x</m> returns the sum of all the differentials of the form -->
    <!--   <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> between the points <m>t=a</m> and <m>t=x</m>. In -->
    <!--   this case that corresponds to the area  between the <m>x</m><ndash/>axis -->
    <!--   and  the graph of the function -->
    <!--   <m>f(t)</m>. -->
    <!-- </p> -->
    <!-- <aside> -->
    <!--   <title>Comment</title> -->
    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     More precisely, it represents the sum of differentials of the -->
    <!--     form <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> between <m>t=a</m> and -->
    <!--     <m>t=x</m>. Although they are closely related area and -->
    <!--     integration are not the same thing.  -->
    <!--   </p> -->
    <!-- </aside> -->

    <paragraphs xml:id="DIGRESSIONDummyVariables">
      <title>DIGRESSION: Dummy Variables </title>

      <p>
        You<rsq/>ve probably noticed our use of both <m>x</m> and
        <m>t</m> that in <xref
        ref="EQUATIONFuncFromInt">equation</xref>. Do we really have
        two variables in play here as it appears we do or is something
        else happening?  Give this some thought before you read on.
      </p>
      <p>
        Don<rsq/>t let this confuse you.  In the formula <m>F(x) =
        \int_{t=a}^xf(t)\dx{t} </m> the variable for the function
        <m>F</m> is <m>x</m>, and the variable for the function
        <m>f</m> is <m>t</m>. The role of <m>t</m> is to define
        <m>f(t)</m> so we can, for instance, display its graph as in
        <xref ref="FIGUREIntegralAsFunction"></xref>.  Notice that
        there is no <m>x</m><ndash/> axis in the figure. The
        graph of <m>f(t)</m> is shown  on the <m>y-t</m> plane.
      </p>
      <p>
        The role of <m>x</m> is the same as the
        role of <m>a</m>, or <m>b</m>.     It locates a position on
        the <m>t</m><ndash/>axis. But since <m>F(x)</m> depends on the
        value of <m>x</m> it is the variable for <m>F</m>.
      </p>
        <p>
          In fact, in a real sense the variable <m>t</m> isn<rsq/>t
          really present. That it appears to be is an artifact of
          defining the function <m>F(x)</m> via an integral. When we
          do this we must have another function to integrate. This forces us
          to use a different variable name to keep things orderly.
        </p>
        <p>
          To see this consider the function
          <me>F(x) = \int_{t=1}^xt\dx{t}</me>. We have
          <me>
            F(x)  = \eval{\frac{t^2}{3}}{t}{1}^x =
            \frac{x^2}{2}-\frac{1}{2}
          </me>
          or 
          <me> F(x) = \frac{x^2}{2}-\frac{1}{2} </me>. 
          Notice that there is no <m>x</m> in the last formula.  For better or
          worse the integration variable (<m>t</m> in this case) is called a
          <term>
            dummy variable.
          </term>

        </p>

        <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
    </paragraphs>
    <p>
      We saw in the previous section  that when computing a definite
      integral it doesn<rsq/>t matter which antiderivative of <m>\int
      f(x)\dx{x}</m> we choose since the constant will subtract out
      anyway.
    </p>
    <p>
      However, there are situations where the particular
      antiderivative used is very important.  
    </p>
    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEIVPViaIntegral">
      <p>
        For example consider the IVP
        <mdn>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONIVPByIntegration">
            \dfdx{y}{x} = 3x^{\frac52 } +x, \amp{}\amp{} y(0)=2
          </mrow>
        </mdn>
        To solve this observe that 
        <me>\int\dx{y} = \int(3x^{\frac52 } +x)\dx{x}</me>. Finding the  most
        general antiderivative of each integral gives
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONIVPByIntegrationSol">y(x) +C_1=\frac67 x^{\frac72} +
        \frac12 x^2 +C_2</men>.
        Strictly speaking <xref ref="EQUATIONIVPByIntegrationSol"></xref> relates
        two multifunctions but suppose <m>y(x)</m> is the particular  solution
of our IVP that we seek. 
Combining the constants we have 
<me>
  y(x) =\frac67 x^{\frac72} +
  \frac12 x^2 + \underbrace{C_2-C_1}_{=C}</me>. We need to  find the
  value of <m>C=C_2-C_1</m> which  satisfies our IVP.
      </p>
      <p>
        From the initial condition we know that 
        <me>
          y(0) = C=2
        </me>
        so 
        <me>
          y(x) =\frac67 x^{\frac72} +
        \frac12 x^2 + 2</me>
      </p>
    </example>

    <exercise>
      

      <task>
        <p>
          Verify that         <me>
          y(x) =\frac67 x^{\frac72} +
          \frac12 x^2 + 2</me>
          is the solution of <xref
          ref="EQUATIONIVPByIntegration">IVP</xref>.
        </p>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>
          Find the solution of <xref ref="EQUATIONIVPByIntegration">IVP</xref>
          if the initial condition is <m>y(4)=0</m>.
        </p>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <example xml:id="EXAMPLEPopDynRedux">
      <title>Population Dynamics, Redux</title>
      <p> 
        For instance in <xref ref="PROBLEMExpGrowth2A">problem</xref>
        you were asked to verify that the solution of the IVP
        <mdn>
          <mrow xml:id="EQUATIONPopDynRedux">
            \dfdx{P}{t}= 0.3P,\amp{}\amp{} P(0)=5.
          </mrow>
        </mdn>
        is <m>P(t)=5e^{0.3t}</m> but we gave no indication how we
        arrived at the solution in  the first place. 
        Since <m>\dfdx{P}{t}= 0.3P</m> is a separable differential equation we now have the
        tools we need to derive the solution ourselves.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since this is separable we see that 
        <men xml:id="EQUATIONIntAsFunction2">
          \int\frac{1}{P}\dx{P}=\int0.3\dx{t}
          </men>. 
          Computing the most general antiderivative of both sides as
          in <xref ref="EXAMPLEIVPViaIntegral"></xref> we have 
          <me>\ln\left(\abs{P}\right) = 0.3t+C</me>.
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Mathematical Notation</title>
        <p>
          The absolute value bars in
          <me>\ln\left(\abs{P}\right) = 0.3t+C</me> are correct, but
          for this problem they turn out to be irrelevant. So we will
          ignore them from here.
        </p>
      </aside>
      <p>
        From our initial condition we have 
        <me>\ln(5) = C</me> so 
        <me>\ln(P)= 0.3t+\ln(5) </me>. But we want to find <m>P</m>
        not <m>\ln(P) </m>. Exponentiating both sides gives 
        <me>e^{\ln\left(P\right)} = e^{0.3t+\ln(5)} = e^{0.3t}\cdot
        e^{\ln(5)} = 5e^{0.3t}</me>
        or
        <me>P(t) = 5e^{0.3t}</me>.
      </p>


      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   Because our initial condition is given at <m>t=0</m> -->
      <!--   we<rsq/>ll try to  compute the indefinite integral on the left -->
      <!--   starting at <m>t=0</m>: <m>F(x) = </m> -->
      <!--   The computing the most general antiderivative of each  side of <xref -->
      <!--   ref="EQUATIONIntAsFunction2">equation</xref>  -->
      <!--   gives -->
      <!--   <me>P(t)=\int\frac{\dx{P}}{P}= 0.03t+C</me>. But this is not very helpful -->
      <!--   and on the left the most gen -->
      <!-- </p> -->
    </example>

    <exercise>
      

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Verify that <m>P(t) = 5e^{0.3t}</m> is the solution of <xref
            ref="EQUATIONPopDynRedux">IVP</xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the solution of <xref ref="EQUATIONPopDynRedux">IVP</xref>
            if the initial condition is <m>y(0)=2</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain what happens if the initial condition is
            <m>y(2)=0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>


    <paragraphs xml:id="DIGRESSIONDefIntAsAccum">
      <title>The Indefinite Integral as an Accumulation Function</title>



      <!-- <p> -->
      <!--   The notation <m>F(x)</m> clearly indicates that <m>F</m> depends  -->
      <!--   on the single variable <m>x</m>. But -->
      <!--   when we  define a function  <m>F(x)</m>, via the formula  -->
      <!--   <me>F(x) = \int_{t=a}^xf(t)\dx{t} </me> we  appear to be have -->
      <!--   used  two variables, <m>x</m> and -->
      <!--   <m>t</m>.  -->

      <!--   It is worth taking a few minutes to understand this quirk of -->
      <!--   integration   notation so it doesn<rsq/>t cause confusion later. -->
      <!-- </p> -->
      <p>
        We have consistently described the definite integral
        <me>F(x)=\int_{t=a}^{b}f(t) \dx{t}</me> as summing the differentials
        <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> <q>starting at <m>x=a</m></q> and <q>ending at
        <m>x</m>.</q>  This suggests that we can think of 
        the function 
        <me>F(x) = \int_{t=a}^x f(t)\dx{t}</me> as an 
        <term>accumulation function</term>. It starts at <m>t=a</m> and
        proceeds to <m>t=b</m>, gathering in and adding  the differentials
        <m>f(t)\dx{t}</m> along the way. Thus, for example the function 
        <me>F(x) = \int_{t=2}^xt \dx{t}</me> in <xref
        ref="EXAMPLESimpleIndefInt"></xref>  
        begins accumulating differentials of the form <m>3t\dx{t}</m>
        at <m>t=2</m> and continues to add them up until it reaches
        the point <m>t=x</m>. The value of <m>F(x)</m> is the sum of
        all of those differentials. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Another formulation of this particular function is 
        <me>F(x) = \frac32 t^2-6</me>. Since this is the same function,
        just reformulated, it is still an accumulation function, but
        the algebraic notation doesn<rsq/>t reflect this as clearly as
        the integral notation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Thinking of the indefinite integral this way can help us
        understand its properties a little better. For instance, we
        saw in <xref ref="THEOREMEvaluateDefInt"></xref> that
        <me>\int_a^bt\dx{t} = \eval{t}{\frac{t^2}{2}}{a}^b</me>. We
        know how to compute this now but let<rsq/>s instead consider
        how the notion of an accumulation function sheds light onto
        the meaning of the computation.
      </p>
      <p>
        First let<rsq/>s define the function <m>F(x)= \int_{t=0}^x
        t\dx{t}</m> which accumulates the area of the red region in
        the following sketch from <m>t=0</m> over to <m>t=x</m>. 
      </p>
      <image source="IC/AccumGraph.png" width="70%">
        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
      </image>
      <p>
        If <m>x=10</m> then <m>F(10)</m> will be the area of the red
        triangle and similarly, <m>F(15)</m> will be the area of the
        larger red and blue triangle. But how could we represent the
        area of the blue region alone?
      </p>
      <aside>
        <title>Note to Bob</title>
        <p>
          I<rsq/>m stopping here for now, My thinking is that we can
          use the accumulation function idea to explain all of the
          Rules for Integration given in <xref
          ref="SECTIONIntegrationRules1"></xref> intuitively.
        </p>
      </aside>
      <p>
        Clearly 
        <me>\text{Area}\left( \text{Blue}\right)
        =\text{Area}\left(\text{Red}+\text{Blue}\right)-\text{Area}\left(
        \text{Red}\right)</me>
        or
        <me>\int_{t=10}^{15}f(t) \dx{t}=F(15)-F(10)</me>
        which is exactly what we would have gotten had we applied
        <xref ref="THEOREMEvaluateDefInt"></xref> to this problem. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Our point here is that it is easier to see why <xref
        ref="THEOREMEvaluateDefInt"></xref> must be true by reasoning
        from <xref ref="FIGUREIntegralAsFunction"></xref>. It is
        useful  to think of integrals, both definite and indefinite,
        in terms of an accumulation function.
      </p>
      <p><alert>END OF DIGRESSION</alert></p>
    </paragraphs>








    <!-- <subsection> -->
    <!--   <title>Try One</title> -->

    <!--   <p> -->
