    <!--         \int_{x=a}^{x=b} f(x)\dx{x}</me> and <me>\int_{a}^{b} f(x)\dx{x}</me>. -->
    <!--     </p> -->
    <!--   </aside> -->

    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     Take care to notice that, although the notations in <xref -->
    <!--     ref="DEFINITIONIndefInt"></xref> and <xref -->
    <!--     ref="DEFINITIONDefInt"></xref> are very similar, but that the -->
    <!--     objects being defined are very different. An <term>indefinite -->
    <!--     integral</term> is a multifunction. A <term>definite -->
    <!--     integral</term> is a number. The reason the notations are so -->
    <!--     similar is that they are both built via (infinite) summation -->
    <!--     of differentials (Cavalieri<rsq/>s <q>lines</q>). -->
    <!--   </p> -->
    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     When we speak of an indefinite integral we are thinking of -->
    <!--     integration as antidifferentiation as in <xref -->
    <!--     ref="SUBSECTIONIntAsAntiDiff"></xref>. -->
    <!--     When we talk about a definite integral we are thinking of -->
    <!--     integration as summation as in <xref -->
    <!--     ref="SUBSECTIONIntegrationAsASum"></xref>. -->
    <!--   </p> -->
    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     In the case of <xref -->
    <!--     ref="EQUATIONIntCav"></xref> we sum the differentials -->
    <!--     <m>2\dx{x}</m> from <m>2</m> to <m>6</m>. -->
    <!--     Because the integral in that example represents the area of a -->
    <!--     <m>4\times 2</m> rectangle result should be <m>4\times -->
    <!--     2=8</m>. -->
    <!--   </p> -->

    <!--   <p> -->
    <!--     But  notice that we haven<rsq/>t yet indicated how we -->
    <!--     would compute this from the integral. -->
