<!-- <p> -->
<!--   As was mentioned before, this result was known to both Newton and -->
<!--   Leibniz and was first publish in a short paper by Leibniz in -->
<!--   1693. The idea is so surprisingly simple and profound, that it -->
<!--   warrants an (apocryphal) story. When Leibniz was a young diplomat -->
<!--   in Paris, he sought Christian Huygens who, at the time, was one -->
<!--   of the most brilliant mathematicians in the world. Leibniz -->
<!--   credited much of his mathematical growth in Paris to Huygens. The -->
<!--   idea for summing differences came to Leibniz from a problem given -->
<!--   to him by Huygens in 1672, namely to compute the following sum -->

<!--   <me>\frac{1}{1\cdot2}+\frac{1}{2\cdot3{}}+\frac{1}{3\cdot4}\cdots</me> -->

<!--   Leibniz recognized that this could be rewritten as -->

<!--   <me>\left(\frac11-\frac12\right)+\left(\frac12-\frac13\right)+\left(\frac13-\frac14\right)+\cdots</me> -->

<!--   and noted that nearly all of the fractions cancelled out leaving -->
<!--   <m>1-\frac{1}{\infty{}}=1-0=1</m>. -->
<!-- </p> -->
